# PLOT 1 #
library(ggplot2)
ggplot(midterm2, aes(x = age)) + geom_density() + labs(x = 'Age', title = 'Density of ages', caption = 'High density of newborns and sixty year olds, with not a lot of teenagers and elder people.')

# PLOT 2 #
ggplot(midterm2, aes(x = provider)) + geom_bar() + labs(x = 'Provider', title = 'Count of Providers', caption = 'Provider 7205(RI Hospital) used the most by a wide margin')

#PLOT 3#
ggplot(midterm2, aes(x = age, y = los)) + geom_point() + labs(x = 'Age', y = 'Length of Stay', title = 'Length of Stay by Age', caption = 'Length of stay is relatively scattered but tends to decrease as age increases.')

#PLOT 4#
ggplot(midterm2, aes(x = age, color = sex)) + geom_density() + labs(x = 'Age', title = 'Age by Gender', caption = 'Males tended to be older while females tended to be younger')

#PLOT 5#
ggplot(midterm2, aes(x = sex, fill = factor(raceethn))) + geom_bar(position = 'dodge') + labs(x = 'sex', title = 'Count of Sex and Race', caption = 'Predominantly white population in the study for both males and females.')

#PLOT 6#

  1. Make an animation
d1 <- midterm2 %>% group_by(moa, provider) %>% summarise(mean = mean(tot))
## `summarise()` regrouping output by 'moa' (override with `.groups` argument)
d2 <- d1 %>% group_by(moa) %>% mutate(rank=rank(-mean)) %>% ungroup()
d3 <- d2 %>% filter(rank <= 10)
library(gganimate)
## Warning: package 'gganimate' was built under R version 3.6.3
p1 <- d3 %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=rank, 
             y=mean, 
             group=provider, 
             fill=provider, 
             label=provider))+ 
     geom_col()+
    geom_text(aes(y = mean, 
                  label = provider), 
              hjust = 1.4)+ 
    coord_flip(clip = "off", 
               expand = FALSE)+
    scale_x_reverse()+
    labs(title='Month {closest_state}',

    theme(plot.title =

          axis.ticks.y=element_blank(),

    transition_states(moa)+

animate(p1, nframes=100, fps=20)

III. Predictive Models

Continue with the data from part I. Use the follows as the target and input variables:

Target Variable: Create the target variable taking value of

  • low cost if the total charge of a patient (tot) is smaller than the median of the total charge, and

  • high cost otherwise.

medtot <- median(midterm2$tot, na.rm = TRUE)
medtot
## [1] 21854
midterm2$target <- case_when(midterm2$tot <medtot ~ 'low cost', TRUE ~ 'high cost')

Input Variables:

  • “age”,“sex”,“raceethn”,“provider”,“moa”,“mod”,“admtype”,“campus”, ‘los’
midterm3 <- select(midterm2, age, sex, raceethn, provider, moa, mod, admtype, campus, los, target)

  1. Train a decision tree using rpart. Plot the decision tree. Plot the variable importance ranked by the tree.
# Train Decision Tree #
library(rpart)

mtdt <- rpart(target ~., data = midterm3_train, control = rpart.control(maxdepth = 3))

  1. Using caret for this question. Set Training Control to be: Use Cross-Validation of 5 folds across all models. Train & tune at least 3 different models (i.e. three different values for method= in the train function of caret). Plot the hyper-parameter tuning plots for each model.
# Random Forest #
library(caret)
trControl = trainControl(method = "cv", number = 5)

mtrf <- train(target~., data = midterm3_train, method = "rf", trControl = trControl)
plot(mtrf)

# Ranger Model #
library(caret)
trControl1 = trainControl(method = "cv", number = 5)

ranger_cv <- train(target~., data = midterm3_train, method = "ranger", trControl = trControl1)
plot(ranger_cv)

# Adaboost Model #
library(caret)
tuneGrid = expand.grid(nIter = 1:5, method = "rf")

trControl2 = trainControl(method = "cv", number = 5)

adaboost_cv <- train(target~., data = midterm3_train, method = "adaboost", trControl = trControl2, tuneGrid = tuneGrid)
plot(adaboost_cv)

  1. Plot the comparison of the models in 2.
results <- resamples(list(forest = mtrf, ranger = ranger_cv, adaboost = adaboost_cv))

bwplot(results)

plot(adaboost_cv2)

results1 <- resamples(list(forest = mtrf2, ranger = ranger_cv1, adaboost = adaboost_cv2))

bwplot(results1)

# Ranger with highest accuracy #
pred <- predict(ranger_cv1, midterm4_test)

cm <- confusionMatrix(data = pred, reference = midterm4_test$target2, positive = "long stay")

cm$overall[1]
